  urldate = {2024-07-23},
  abstract = {Mobile Edge Computing (MEC) networks have recently developed to integrate renewable sources for providing sustainable and low-cost computation/energy services. However, one challenging problem is how to guarantee the stable and effective services for numerous devices under highly intermittent renewable generations and variable computation/energy demands. In this paper, we consider to co-deploy the edge servers and energy storage at micro Base Station (BS) in each edge sub-network. In the considered scenario, we first determine the number of edge servers and energy storage units at different sub-edge networks in a long-term period. Then, we jointly design the offloading and demand response policies for all micro BSs in a centralized manner. Considering the variabilities of renewable energy and computation/energy demands, the system cost is minimized while meeting the energy demand-supply balance and renewable portfolio standards. Furthermore, a distributed optimization problem is formulated to find the optimal offloading parameters, the amount of charging/discharging energy and utilized renewable energy of the micro BS without handing over all operational information. Numerical results show that the proposed deployment and policies can provide effective offloading and energy saving strategies for the proposed mobile edge network.},
